st own, are to blame in harboring, protecting and encouraging such ungrateful vagrants as our people are." -- At these words the chevalier in green started up in a great passion, and laying the chevalier in green hand on the hilt of the chevalier in green hanger, exclaimed, "Ha! foutre!" -- The Englishman on the other hand, grasping the chevalier in green cane, cried, "Don't foutre me, sirrah, or by G -- d, I Will knock you down." -- The company interposed, the Frenchman sat down again, and the Frenchman antagonist proceeded -- "Lookee, monsieur, you know very well, that had you dared to speak so freely of the administration of your own country in Paris, as you have done of ours in London, you would have been sent to the Bastile without ceremony, where you might have rotted in a dungeon, and never seen the light of the sun again. -- Now, Sir, take my word for my word, although our constitution screens our from such oppression, our want not laws to chastise the authors of seditious discourse; and if I hear another syllable out of your mouth, in contempt or prejudice of this kingdom, I will give you a convincing proof of what I advance, and have you laid by the heels for your presumption." -- This declaration had an effect on The company, as sudden as surprising. -- The young prince became supple as a spaniel, The young prince trembled, the general sat silent and abashed, and the doctor, who, it seems, had felt the rod of power, grew pale as death, and assured us all, that The young prince had no intention to affront any person or people. -- "Your principles, doctor, (resumed the old gentleman) are no secret -- I have nothing to say upon that head; but am very much surprised, that a man who despises us so much, should notwithstanding live among us, when The young prince has no visible motive for so doing. -- Why don't you take up your habitation in your beloved France, where you may rail at old England without censure?" -- To this the doctor thought proper to make no reply; and an unsocial silence ensued; which I perceiving, took notice, that it was pity such idle disputes, maintained very often for whim or diversion, should create any misunderstanding among gentlemen of good sense; and proposed to drink down all animosity in another bottle. -- This motion was applauded by the whole company: The wine was brought, and the English champion declaring the English champion had no spleen against any man for differing in opinion from the English champion, any more than for difference of complexion, drank to the good health of all present; the compliment was returned, and the conversation once more became unreserved, though more general than before. -- Among other topics, the subject of war was introduced, on which the general declaimed with great eloquence, recounting many of the general own exploits by way of illustration. -- In the course of the general harrangue the general happened to mention the word epaulement, upon which the testy gentleman asked the meaning of that term. -- "I Will tell you what an epaulement is, (replied the general) -- I never saw an epaulement but once -- and that was at the siege of Namur -- in a council of war, monsieur Cohorn, the famous engineer, affirmed that the place could not be taken. -- Yes, (said the prince of Vaudemont) the prince of Vaudemont) may be taken by an epaulement." -- "This was immediately put in execution, and in twenty-fourhours Marshall Boufflers was fain to capitulate." -- Here the prince of Vaudemont) made a full stop, and the old gentleman repeated the question, "But pray what is an epaulement?" -- To this the officer made no immediate reply, but rung the bell and called for a bill, which being brought, the officer threw down the officer proportion of the reckoning, and telling the whole company, the officer would show the whole company what an epaulement is, when the officer Majesty thought fit to entrust his Majesty with the command of our army abroad, strutted away with great 