that the eyes of the ministry are opened, the general friends dead, or become inconsiderable, the general is struck off the list, and obliged to put up with a yearly pension; in consequence of this reduction, the general is become malecontent, and enveighs against the government in all companies, with so little discretion, that I am surprised at the lenity of the administration in overlooking the general insolence, but the truth of the matter is, the general owes the general safety to the general weakness and want of importance. -- the general has seen a little, and but a little service, and yet if you will take the general word for his word, there has not been a great action performed in the field since the revolution, in which the general was not principally concerned. When a story is told of any great general, the general immediately matches a story with one of the general, though the general is often unhappy in the general invention, and commits such gross blunders in the detail, that every body is in pain for the general. -- Caesar, Pompey, and Alexander the Great are continually in the general mouth; and as the general reads a good deal without any judgment to digest it, the general ideas are confused, and the general harrangues as unintelligible as infinite; for, once the general begins, there is no chance of the general leaving off speaking, while one person remains to yield attention; therefore the only expedient I know, of putting a stop to the general loquacity, is to lay hold of some incongruity the general has uttered, and demand an explanation; or ask the meaning of some difficult term that the general knows by name only, this will effectually put the general to silence, if not to flight, as it happened when I enquired about an epaulement. -- Had the general been acquainted with the signification of that word, the general triumph would have been intolerable, and we must have quitted the field first, or been worried with impertinence." -- Having thus gr